    "Unknown": "). Possibly once he became king, he would develop the mentality and disposition of a king and perhaps be better than the preceding ruler. But the \u201cearth trembles\u201d when a servant is king; unaccustomed to such dignity, he might become a power-hungry tyrant and oppressive ruler (Greenstone, 324, suggests the example of Hitler). The second, a fool who is full of food, describes a fool who becomes prosperous but continues to be boorish and irreligious. But now he is overbearing and, worse yet, finds time hanging heavy on his hands. The third is the unloved woman who gets married (",
    "Arthur W. Pink": "), and these were passed through \"two rings of gold on the ends of the breastplate.\" Thus the people of God (as represented by their names) were chained to the high priest! \"The chains were wreathen and twisted like a rope, for both words are used; wreathen, interwoven. The same word is used in Judges [v_Psa_12_3] 15:13, 14; 16:11, 12;\n22. It is indeed striking to see that in the above, Aaron `[char_Aaron_Exo_6]` and his sons took no active part at all; from first to last they were passive in the hands of another. They did not minister, but were ministered unto. Much was done for them and to them; but they themselves did nothing. Standing in God\u2019s stead, Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` did all for them. It was by his word that they were chosen and brought. It was by his hands they were washed, clothed and anointed. It was Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` also who brought the bullock for the sin-offering, as \"the ram of consecration.\" So too the application of the blood to the several parts of their bodies was the work of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` (\nv. 22): he it was who \"filled their hands\"\u2014he gave, they received (",
